.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-59-### Constraints
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-60-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-61-- Compiled routing must stay byte-identical to legacy for matched hubs. This program never changes what routes.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:62:- The three frozen benchmark scorer files (`router-replay.cjs`, `score-skill-benchmark.cjs`, `load-playbook-scenarios.cjs`) are pinned and never edited.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-63-- `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` is absent from `ENV-REFERENCE.md`, which CLAUDE.md section 6 mandates as the source of truth for flag defaults. Flipping an undocumented flag violates that mandate.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-64-- The serve-time shim recomputes each hub's decision from live config and falls back to a `{ servingAuthority: "legacy" }` sentinel on any mismatch (`compiled-route.cjs:36-39`), which the advisor maps to `undefined` (`advisor-recommend.ts:351`). Editing a hub reverts it to legacy until re-minted, with nothing to observe the reversion.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-65-
--
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-70-<!-- ANCHOR:adr-001-decision -->
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-71-### Decision
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-72-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:73:**We chose**: Treat global default-on as the final outcome of a four-step program (P0 through P4), not a one-line default change made now.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-74-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:75:**How it works**: P0 documents the flag in `ENV-REFERENCE.md` and makes the verify harness distinguish drift-to-legacy from breakage plus a per-hub serving-status readout. P1 adds a drift-detection CI that recomputes each hub's live hash against its minted manifest and fails re-mint-required. P2 canaries default-on in one env profile while the repo default stays off. P3 replaces the two hardcoded allowlists with a data-driven eligibility rule (see ADR-002). P4 flips the repo default hub-by-hub, keeping `=0` as the documented kill-switch. The flip becomes worthwhile precisely when compiled routing does something legacy cannot (a consumed decision, a caught drift), which P0 through P3 create.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-76-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:77:**Settlement**: This ruling is settled on the merits of the analysis above (the five premise-failures and the resolver coupling), as the session directive to settle the decision using the fresh-Opus analysis requires. It is a reversible documentation decision: no runtime change follows from it, and the operator may override to flip-now at any time. Acceptance settles the sequencing (phased) only; a separate operator go-ahead gates the start of P0 implementation.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-78-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-79-<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-001-decision -->
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-80-
--
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-85-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-86-| Option | Pros | Cons | Score |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-87-|--------|------|------|-------|
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:88:| **Phased P0 to P4 (chosen)** | Reversible at every step; drift caught by CI not production; flag documented before it is load-bearing; the flip lands when it carries benefit | Four phases of enabling work before the headline default flips | 9/10 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-89-| Flip the repo default now | One-line change; matches the literal goal wording | Zero routing benefit (additive metadata only); normalizes silent drift; inverts the kill-switch (absence becomes compiled); violates the ENV-REFERENCE governance mandate | 3/10 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-90-| Abandon compiled routing | Removes the drift surface entirely | Discards a built, proven, reversible system and the parity work behind it; loses the future benefit the phased path unlocks | 2/10 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-91-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:92:**Why this one**: The destination (compiled as the effective default) is not rejected, it is sequenced. Flipping today trades governance and observability surface for a benefit that is currently zero, so the correct move is to build the benefit and the safety net first, then flip. The steelman for flipping now is honest and recorded: if compiled cannot help and cannot hurt routing, the only net effects are the ones that can hurt, so flip it once compiled does something legacy cannot. That condition is exactly what P0 through P3 establish.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-93-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-94-<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-001-alternatives -->
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-95-
--
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-101-**What improves**:
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-102-- The eventual flip is observable: a per-hub readout shows compiled-serving vs legacy-fallback vs drifted, so a red signal means breakage rather than routine churn.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-103-- Drift is caught in CI at edit time, not discovered in production after a hub silently reverts to legacy.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:104:- The kill-switch stays meaningful: `=0` remains the documented control, and variable-absence keeps its safe legacy meaning until the P4 flip deliberately changes it.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-105-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-106-**What it costs**:
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-107-- Four phases of enabling work precede the headline default change. Mitigation: each phase ships standalone value (docs, CI, canary, single-sourced eligibility) rather than being pure overhead.
--
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-110-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-111-| Risk | Impact | Mitigation |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-112-|------|--------|------------|
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:113:| Operator overrides to flip now | M | The fallback is genuinely fail-safe today, so an early flip is survivable; but P0 documentation and observability should still land first to satisfy governance and avoid a two-meaning red signal |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md-114-| Phased path stalls mid-program | L | Each phase is independently valuable and reversible; stalling leaves the repo in a strictly better documented and observable state than today |
